## Follow-up: notdiamond custom_router
Audit (reviewer asked to check for missing integrations) found notdiamond/
custom_router.py exposes two public @weave.op helpers — train_router and
evaluate_router — that call the NotDiamond client but weren't stamped (they use
the bare @weave.op decorator, not the settings.op_settings path). Added
NOTDIAMOND_INTEGRATION = library_integration("notdiamond") and attributes=
NOTDIAMOND_INTEGRATION.as_attributes() on both decorators. Left the 3 inner
_DummyEvalModel.predict ops unstamped on purpose: they're eval scaffolding over
precomputed dataframes, not notdiamond calls. ruff + ast clean; notdiamond lib
not installed locally so not runtime-tested.

## Test coverage added (follow-up to reviewer "missing tests")

The original commit only asserted the integration block on openai. Added
shape-confirming `attributes["integration"]` assertions to one existing
cassette/call test per op-based integration:

- Specific-call style (assert on the integration's call directly): anthropic,
  cerebras, cohere, groq, litellm, mistral, google_genai, vertexai, huggingface,
  instructor, bedrock.
- Robust style (filter fetched calls to name==<vendor> before asserting): autogen,
  crewai, dspy, smolagents, langchain_nvidia, fastmcp, gepa, verifiers,
  notdiamond/tracing. These agent-framework tests ALSO capture sub-integration
  calls (litellm/openai/huggingface) that carry their OWN integration block, so a
  naive all()-over-all-stamped-calls would fail — must filter to the vendor first.
- notdiamond/custom_router: asserts the module-level train_router/evaluate_router
  @weave.op helpers' public `.attributes["integration"]` directly (no call needed).

Each assert checks: name == <vendor>, truthy version (= weave SDK version),
meta.package_name == <distribution name> (e.g. mistral->mistralai,
cerebras->cerebras-cloud-sdk, bedrock->boto3, vertexai->google-cloud-aiplatform).

